. whats the difference between the two, other than going with the Xircom will add $140 to the price?<br><br><br>Also, they have an optional thing for Network cards, being:<br>1. None<br>2. Internal miniPCI Dell TrueMobile 1150 Wireless Networking (Wi-Fi Certified) <br>3. Xircom® 10/100 Ethernet II, PC Card <br>4. Dell Truemobile 1150, 802.11b PC-Card (Wi-Fi Certified) <br><br>So.. if I go with the standerd option for a Modem &lt;opt 1 up above&gt; and then with Opt 3 for Network cards &lt;+$119&gt;, saving myself $21, how is that going to be any different than just going with Opt 2 for Modems? Will that take up more room or something? And if I go with Opt 2 for modems, do I need to even opt for an additional Network card, or will that have already satisfied my need for a Network hookup? <br><br><br>So that's my big main problem/question I'm having... also, just as an aside, any suggestions on a good carrying case?<br><br>Thanks all<br>Yuber <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#fbe5b4><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub31.ezboard.com/umilossilvertune.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Milos Silvertune</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Soldier of Misfortune</span><br>  Posts: 186<br> <font color=#993300>(12/16/01 5:09:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub31.ezboard.com/fforgottengrailkeepersfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=144.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Need some Labtop help/info..</span><hr size=1> With option 1, your PCMCIA slots will be free to use for other things. <br><br>With option 2, the NIC/modem will be hogging it up. I believe the Realport is a double thickness card (forgot what they called that specifically) that is going to hog up both PCMCIA slots.<br><br>Thats not necessarily bad.....I've used a laptop for the last 3 years for work, and the only thing I've used my PCMCIA slots for is NICs/modems anyways.<br><br>Regarding your second question, it sounds like both options 1 and 2 provide you with both the network interface and modem. So if it was up to me, save the dough and go with option 1. You'll be getting 100mb ethernet, 56kbps modem capability, and still have available PCMCIA slots.<br><br>Targus makes great laptop bags. <p><br><br><img src="http://mdr-nhl.home.att.net/aruthsig.gif" border="0"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#fed995><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub31.ezboard.com/usulyen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sulyen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>cRaZy Edare's<br>Armor Emporium!</span><br>  Posts: 205<br> <font color=#993300>(12/16/01 7:55:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub31.ezboard.com/fforgottengrailkeepersfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=144.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Need some Labtop help/info..</span><hr size=1> A laptop has a standard method for adding small peripherals( modem, network, small hard drive,etc).  These are PC-Card slots.  This supersedes the term PCMCIA slots. Most laptops provide 2, type 2 slots, or a type 3 device will take both slots at once. The type kinda refers to the size of the PC-Card you can plug in.<br><br>By going with the internal parts, you leave these slots open for other uses, if the need arises.<br><br>Just to add concerning the network cards:<br><br>Options 2 and 4 are about wireless networking.  This means no cable needed to connect you to the network. Of course, this requires a &quot;Hub&quot; that supports this system.  802.11b is a wireless networking standard.<br><br>Option 2 is internal to the laptop and option 4 uses one of the PC-Card slots.<br><br><br>Option 3 is a type 2 card that plugs into one of the PC-Card slots.<br><br>Important considerations in a laptop.<br><br>1.  Do you like the keyboard layout?<br>2.  Do you like the built in pointing device, trackpad, mouse button, etc.<br>3.  Battery life.  If you are going to be mobile this can be very important.<br>4.  Device bays.  This is a generic term describing removable parts of the laptop.  Does the laptop have the required peripherals?  Do you need a floppy?  Do you need a CD/DVD/CDRW player? Do you need a zip disk?  Using device bays some manufacturers let you swap these devices around to the configuration you want. Say 2 batteries if you dont need the CD, or no battery if you are plugged in all the time.<br>5.  Laptops are easy to break, look for a sturdy one.<br>6.  Display size, laptop size/weight.<br> <p><br><hr>Sulyen, 54th Pathfinder,Ravens Wings,Tribunal<br>Edare, 34th Armsman, Forgotten Grail Keepers, Guinevere<br><br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#fbe5b4><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub31.ezboard.com/usildroni.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sildroni</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Zannah McZannah<br>of the Clan McZannah</span><br>  Posts: 133<br> <font color=#993300>(12/17/01 11:01:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub31.ezboard.com/fforgottengrailkeepersfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=144.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Need some Labtop help/info..</span><hr size=1> go with the Xircom card.<br><br>Sure - you use up both of your PC cardslots for one device, but you'll never have to look for dongles to connect with cause the Network and voice drops connect directly into the card.<br><br>Get a laptop with everything inside it already.<br><br>a big strong pally like you dosent need a sub 5lb notebook - and the reality is you'll have to carry it all with you anyway if the items are external and connect to the laptop.  Takes up more desktop space and really defeats the purpose of 'laptop'.<br><br><br>I personally dislike trackball (dustcollecter) mouses in laptops - followed closely by touchpads.  I like IBM's little thumbscrew thingy - or whatever techie term they use.  I know several other companies were using the same type of pointing device, but not sure if they are an optional item.<br><br>Max the RAM<br>Max the HD space<br>DvD - this'll let you watch movies and will prolly get you some decent video too - maybe enough to play DAoC on lunch break <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>Add a pinstripe...with a pulsebeat in it!!<br><br>or...do whatever you want - you'll ultimately be the one you're decisions effect.<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Zannah</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#fed995><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub31.ezboard.com/utheodaen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Theodaen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font color=#993300>(12/17/01 11:54:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub31.ezboard.com/fforgottengrailkeepersfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=144.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://ebonrose.hypermart.net/Theo1.jpg width=80 height=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Need some Labtop help/info..</span><hr size=1> Aren't we forgetting the graphics component..  They are buildig 3D graphics laptop cards as well now... The Standard ATI Rage Mobilitiy does all 3D in software and it can be a dog.. although in 640 x 480 and all effects off, I was able to EQ over a phone line... <br><br>AND ditto all that zannah said..   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#fbe5b4><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub31.ezboard.com/umilossilvertune.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Milos Silvertune</A>&nbsp; <IMG 